The paper deals with the parameterized complexity of the $k$-Clustering problem, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry and machine learning. The problem involves partitioning a set of vectors into $k$ clusters such that the sum of distances between each vector and its cluster center is minimized. The paper considers different distance orders $p$ and shows that the parameterized complexity strongly depends on $p$. This suggests that the paper could be relevant to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.DM (discrete mathematics), cs.CG (computational geometry), cs.CC (computational complexity), and cs.AI (artificial intelligence). Among these, cs.DS and cs.DM are the most likely categories, as the paper deals with algorithmic and combinatorial aspects of the problem. However, the paper also has implications for machine learning and optimization, which could make cs.AI a relevant category as well. Finally, cs.CG and cs.CC are also possible categories, as the problem involves geometric and complexity-theoretic considerations.
